      <h2>The friction was never creation. It was output.</h2>

      <p>I've always had more ideas than I could ship. As someone with ADHD, I think in systems, connections, and frameworks constantly — but the gap between thinking something and publishing it has always been where things die. Not from lack of quality. From lack of throughput.</p>

      <p>I didn't want a ghostwriter. I wanted a <strong>production partner</strong> — something that could take my rough thinking, my voice notes, my messy frameworks, and help me shape them into publishable artifacts at the speed my brain actually moves.</p>

      <p>That's what Claude is to this site.</p>

      <h2>Perspective injection</h2>

      <p>The method I use isn't "prompting" in the way most people mean it. I call it <strong>perspective injection</strong> — feeding an autonomous AI agent not just instructions, but a point of view. My background. My frameworks. My taste. My values. The way I think about remix culture, product strategy, attention design, ADHD systems.</p>

      <p>The AI doesn't generate my ideas. It receives my perspective and helps me express it at scale. Every article starts with my thesis, my structure, my examples. Claude helps me iterate the prose, refine the arguments, catch weak thinking, and produce the final output.</p>

      <p>Think of it as the difference between a photographer and their camera. The camera doesn't have vision. But a great camera in skilled hands produces work neither could alone.</p>

      <h2>Why I'm confident, not defensive</h2>

      <p>I studied philosophy before ChatGPT existed. I learned to write by hand-crafting arguments about epistemology, ethics, and the nature of consciousness. I know what my voice sounds like. I know when an argument is lazy. I know when a metaphor lands.</p>

      <p>That's exactly why I can use AI effectively. The people who should be cautious about AI writing are those who haven't developed their own voice yet. If you know what good looks like, AI is an amplifier. If you don't, it's a crutch.</p>

      <p>I refine relentlessly. Most articles on this site go through multiple passes where I reshape, rewrite, cut, and redirect. The AI handles production. I handle perspective.</p>

      <h2>The accountability engine</h2>

      <p>Here's the part people don't talk about: using AI this way actually makes me <em>more</em> accountable, not less. When you can produce at speed, you lose the excuse of "I'll get to it eventually." The bottleneck shifts from execution to taste — and taste is a harder problem.</p>

      <p>I wanted to build in public, share what I'm learning, and create a body of work that captures my thinking at ISB and beyond. AI made that possible at the pace my brain demands. Without it, these articles would still be voice notes on my phone.</p>

      <p>The choice was never "AI or authentic." It was "AI or silence." I chose output.</p>

      <h2>What this means in practice</h2>

      <p>Every piece on this site follows a process:</p>

      <p><strong>1. I define the thesis.</strong> What am I arguing? What framework am I introducing? What experience am I drawing from? This is always mine.</p>

      <p><strong>2. I provide the perspective.</strong> My background, my examples, my voice, my taste. The AI operates within the constraints of my thinking, not its own.</p>

      <p><strong>3. Claude helps produce the draft.</strong> Structure, prose, transitions, interactive components. It handles the production pipeline.</p>

      <p><strong>4. I refine relentlessly.</strong> Multiple passes. Cutting what doesn't sound like me. Sharpening what does. The final voice is mine — shaped by a tool, not replaced by one.</p>

      <p><strong>5. The code and design are collaborative.</strong> This entire site — the layout, the interactive components, the SVG covers, the design system — is built through human-AI collaboration. I direct. Claude engineers. We iterate together.</p>

      <h2>An advocate for the method</h2>

      <p>I'm not disclosing AI use because I have to. I'm disclosing it because I believe this is how creative work will increasingly happen, and I want to be honest about the process while the norms are still forming.</p>

      <p>The best creative work has always been collaborative. Directors work with cinematographers. Musicians work with producers. Writers work with editors. AI is the newest collaborator in a long tradition of human-tool partnerships that extend creative capability.</p>

      <p>If you're interested in the principles behind how I work with AI, I've written them down as <a href="/ai-rules/">Rahil's 10 Rules of Using AI</a>.</p>

      <hr />

